   153	/// Lower bound on σ in *response-scaled* units for the location-scale GAMLSS
   154	/// noise link σ = LOGB_SIGMA_FLOOR + exp(η). Mirrors mgcv's `gaulss(b=0.01)`
   155	/// default. The Gaussian location-scale log-likelihood
   156	///
   157	///   ℓ = −½ Σ (y−μ)²/σ² − Σ log σ
   158	///
   159	/// is unbounded *above* as σ → 0 with μ → y on any single observation
   160	/// (the −log σ term goes to +∞), so the *negative* log-likelihood is
   161	/// unbounded below and the unconstrained MLE does not exist. With
   162	/// σ ≥ b > 0 the −log σ term is bounded above by −log b, so the joint
   163	/// penalized objective stays finite for any finite data and the working
   164	/// weight 1/σ² is bounded by 1/b².
   165	///
   166	/// # Scale invariance
   167	///
   168	/// This 0.01 looks absolute but is *operationally* scale-relative: the GAMLSS
   169	/// fit driver in `main.rs` first computes
   170	/// `response_scale = sample_std(y).max(1e-6)` and rescales `y → y / response_scale`
   171	/// before fitting (see `gaussian_saved_fit_scale_for_role` and the
   172	/// `y_scaled` construction). The reported σ in response units is then
   173	///
   174	///   σ_response = (LOGB_SIGMA_FLOOR + exp(η)) · response_scale,
   175	///
   176	/// so the response-scale floor is `0.01 · sample_std(y)` — exactly 1 % of the
   177	/// robust spread of `y`. Under a rescaling `y → c·y` the prefit divides by `c`
   178	/// again, leaving the dimensionless internal floor unchanged. The single
   179	/// lingering breakage is the global underflow guard `response_scale.max(1e-6)`:
   180	/// if the user feeds responses with `sample_std(y) < 1e-6` the floor stops
   181	/// tracking the data scale. That is a deliberate guard against a pathological
   182	/// constant-y input rather than a model assumption, and 1e-6 sits well below
   183	/// any sensible measurement-noise floor.
   184	pub const LOGB_SIGMA_FLOOR: f64 = 0.01;
